Cholera Trigger Analysis

Pauline N.

2025-08-26

Introduction

This document contains analysis used to create an alert system using the WHO bulletins for cholera. It is done by country and checks for common indicators of an uptick in cases.

Global Cholera Trigger Options:

  1. Use the DRC trigger:

    • Level 3 alert sustained for 3 weeks
    • Level 3 defined as either:
      1. 4x increase compared to baseline, or
      2. Value above the 99th percentile

  2. Use the old cumulative methodology (as included by Seth in the Signals system)

  3. Use the Signals methodology:

    • Alert when current value is higher than any point in the past 12 months

  4. Use a 3-year rolling average of weekly increases

Exploration of using the CFR or the Number of Deaths as well.

Methodology 3

Methodology 4

Create a 3-year rolling average of weekly caseload with a minimum of 500 new cases.

Timelines for Method 4.

Challenges with the Rolling Average Method (3-year baseline)

  1. Data Gaps and Inconsistencies
  • Many countries lack continuous weekly data over 3 years.
  • Missing weeks break the continuity, making the rolling mean less reliable.
  1. Short Time Series
  • For countries with only 1–2 years of data, the method results in a simple mean value.
  1. Small spikes in cases can exceed the rolling mean, generating alerts even when there is no meaningful outbreak.
  2. Multiple Alerts for the Same Event

- Warning alert: 99th percentile
